        "excerpt": "\"Your customer's car isn't the only thing that needs a lock.\" Auto shops face unique data privacy risks in 2026.",
        "content": "\n\n<h3>Data Privacy Risks for Auto Repair Shops</h3>\n<p>The Pitch: \"Your customer's car isn't the only thing that needs a lock.\"</p>\n\n<h3>The Problem</h3>\n<p>Shops use spreadsheets or paper files to track customers. Two big fears:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Data breaches:</strong> Customer info stolen.</li>\n<li><strong>Losing control:</strong> Locked out of their own records.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Buildify = The Iron Vault</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Data stolen?</strong> Bank-level encryption.</li>\n<li><strong>Unauthorized access?</strong> Mandatory MFA + role-based logins.</li>\n<li><strong>Losing ownership?</strong> You keep the encryption keys.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Small auto repair shops hold sensitive details</h3>\n<p>Customers' payment details, Vehicle VIN and more. Many auto shops still rely on spreadsheets or notebooks leaving them vulnerable.</p>\n\n<h3>3 Tips to close the security gap:</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Encrypt Everything:</strong> Choose software that encrypts (scrambles) data when sent and when stored. If the data falls into the wrong hands, they won't be able to read it because only you can unscramble the data using your encryption key.</li>\n<li><strong>Oversee your keys:</strong> Choose a system where you control the encryption key, not the software company. This ensures that the data is your own, no matter what.</li>\n<li><strong>Use Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA):</strong> Add a second layer of security (like a code sent to your phone) so only you can access your shop's data, even if a password is guessed.</li>\n</ol>",
